o check if there are any issues with the eventbus consumer that I should flag.\n
\nLet me re-read the consumer code to check for a potential issue I noticed:\n\n
In `redisStreamConsumer.handleMessage`:\n```go\n// 业务处理\nif err := c.process
or.Process(ctx, event); err != nil {\n    log.Context(ctx).Warnw("process event 
failed", "event_id", event.EventId, "error", err)\n    c.retryOrDLQ(ctx, streamK
ey, msg, event)\n    return\n}\n\n// 标记已处理\nif err := c.checker.MarkProcess
ed(ctx, event.EventId); err != nil {\n    log.Context(ctx).Warnw("mark processed
failed", "event_id", event.EventId, "error", err)\n}\n\n// 发送 ACK\nc.ack(ctx, 
streamKey, msg.ID)\n```\n\nThe issue here is: if `MarkProcessed` fails, the mess
age is still ACKed. This means if the consumer crashes after ACK but before the 
key was set, the message could be redelivered to another consumer. However, sinc
e `Process` already succeeded, the event would be processed twice. But wait - th
ere\'s an idempotency check at the beginning of `handleMessage`, so when redeliv
ered, it would see `processed=true` and just ACK. But if `MarkProcessed` failed,
the key might not exist, so the redelivery would process it again.\n\nThis is a 
potential issue, but it\'s a common trade-off in distributed systems. The messag
e is already ACKed after successful processing, so at-least-once delivery is mai
ntained but duplicate processing is possible during the MarkProcessed failure wi
ndow.\n\nAnother issue: in `retryOrDLQ`, after retrying, the message is re-queue
d with `retry_count+1`. But the retry count is stored in the message values. Whe
n the message is later read by XReadGroup, `msg.Values["retry_count"]` is a stri
ng (because Redis stores values as strings), and it\'s parsed with `strconv.Atoi
`. This seems correct.\n\nWait, there\'s another potential issue in `redisStream
Consumer.consumePartition`:\n```go\nconsumerID := c.config.ConsumerID\nif consum
erID == "" {\n    consumerID = fmt.Sprintf("consumer-%d", time.Now().UnixNano())
\n}\n```\n\nThis generates a new consumerID every time a partition goroutine sta
rts. If the process restarts, all partitions get new consumer IDs, meaning pendi
ng messages from old consumers won\'t be claimed by the new ones automatically. 
The `processPending` phase reads messages with ID "0" which gets all pending mes
sages for the group, regardless of consumer. So this should be okay because `pro
cessPending` handles PEL messages before normal consumption.\n\nActually, `XRead
Group` with "0" reads pending messages for THIS consumer, not for the whole grou
p. If consumerID changes on restart, pending messages from the old consumerID re
main unclaimed. This is a real issue! The pending messages would build up in PEL
and never be processed by new consumers with different IDs.\n\nHowever, looking 
at the design, the consumer is meant to be run as a long-running process. If it 
crashes and restarts, it should use the same ConsumerID. The config allows setti
ng ConsumerID, and the default is empty string which generates a random one. Thi
s means by default, restarts will lose pending messages.\n\nThis is a significan
t issue that should be flagged.\n\nLet me also check the `EventConsumerServer.St
art` method:\n```go\ngo func() {\n    defer func() {\n        if r := recover();
r != nil {\n            log.Context(ctx).Errorw("event consumer panic recovered"
, "panic", r)\n        }\n    }()\n    if err := s.consumer.Start(ctx); err != n
il {\n        log.Context(ctx).Errorw("event consumer stopped with error", "erro
r", err)\n    }\n}()\n```\n\nIf `Start` panics, the panic is recovered and logge
d, but the consumer doesn\'t restart. The goroutine just exits. In a production 
system, the consumer should probably restart or the process should exit so Kuber
netes can restart it.\n\nAnother issue in `internalEventBus.Publish`:\n```go\nfo
r _, s := range subs {\n    h := s.handler\n    b.pool.Go(func() {\n        if e
rr := h(ctx, event); err != nil {\n            log.Context(ctx).Warnw("event han
dler failed", ...)\n        }\n    })\n}\n```\n\nThe `ctx` and `event` are captu
red by the closure. Since `event` is a pointer, if the caller modifies it after 
Publish returns, the handler might see inconsistent state. But this is unlikely 
since events are typically immutable after creation. However, `ctx` is also capt
ured - if the parent ctx is cancelled, the child goroutines will see the cancell
ed context. This is actually fine for most cases.\n\nActually, wait - the `event
` pointer is shared across all goroutines. If one handler modifies the event, ot
hers could be affected. The events should ideally be treated as immutable.\n\nLe
t me check one more thing: the `gopool` usage. `gopool.NewPool("eventbus-pool", 
1024, gopool.NewConfig())` creates a pool with 1024 workers. If all workers are 
busy, `Go()` blocks until a worker is available. This could potentially block th
e Publish caller if many events are being processed. But `Publish` doesn\'t wait
for goroutines to complete, it just submits them. If the pool is full, `Go()` wi
ll block. This could be a performance concern under high load.\n\nLet me also ch
eck if there\'s a potential deadlock or goroutine leak in the eventbus consumer.
The `consumePartition` loops until `stopCh` is closed or `ctx.Done()`. When `sto
pCh` is closed, the goroutine exits and `wg.Done()` is called. This seems correc
t.\n\nActually, looking more carefully at `Start`:\n```go\n// 阶段1: 统一确保所
有 consumer group 创建成功\nstreamKeys := make([]string, 0, c.config.Partition)\
nfor i := 0; i < c.config.Partition; i++ {\n    streamKey := fmt.Sprintf("%s:%d"
, c.config.StreamKeyPrefix, i)\n    if err := c.ensureConsumerGroup(ctx, streamK
ey); err != nil {\n        return fmt.Errorf("ensure consumer group failed for %
s: %w", streamKey, err)\n    }\n    streamKeys = append(streamKeys, streamKey)\n
}\n\n// 阶段2: 统一启动所有分区 goroutine\nfor _, streamKey := range streamKeys 
{\n    c.wg.Add(1)\n    go c.consumePartition(ctx, streamKey)\n}\n\nc.wg.Wait()\
